Analyzing World Happines Data¶

By: Matthew McIntyre¶

In this tutorial, I will analyze data from the World Happiness Report for 2021. The World Happiness Report contains happiness rankings of countries around the world. The polling to collect the happiness data is done by Gallup and published in the Gallup World Poll (GWP). The GWP has a section about global happiness data called the "Gallup Global Happiness Center".

The goal of this tutorial is to analyze factors that affect the happiness in a country. During this tutorial, I will walk through the phases of the data science pipeline to help me analyze the data and derive useful insights from that analysis.

The education index table has scores from 1990 to 2019 but I want data for 2021. I can use the historical data to construct a linear model that can predict the scores for 2021 for each country.

In [1195]:
# map the country to the 2021 predicted score
edu_score_2021 = pd.Series(dtype = 'float32')

plot_count = 0

for country, info in education_index_df.groupby('Country'):
    # get scores and years from each country, ignoring years where the country has no score
    X = np.array(info.loc[info['Score'] != '..', 'Year'])
    y = np.array(info.loc[info['Score'] != '..', 'Score'])
    # use the year as a predictor for the score and make a prediction for the 2021 score using linear regression
    lin_model = LinearRegression()
    lin_model.fit(X.reshape(-1, 1), y)
    # make a scatter plot of year vs score for each country to see if the relationship is linear
    if plot_count < 10:
        plt.figure(figsize = (3, 3))
        plt.scatter(X, y)
        plt.title(country)
        plt.show()
    # pair up the country with its 2021 predicted score in the Series object
    edu_score_2021.loc[country.strip()] = lin_model.predict(np.array(2021).reshape(1, -1))[0]
    plot_count += 1

In the above code, I use the DataFrame groupby() method to loop through each country individually and make a linear regression predction for their 2021 education index score. I use the years to predict the score. I also produced a scatter plot for each country where year is on the x axis and the score is on the y axis. I did this to verify that there is a linear relationship beween year and score. I only displayed plots for the first 10 countries because plotting for all countries takes up a lot of space. The country and predicted 2021 score are paired up in a pandas Series object.

Now that I have the predicted scores for 2021, I can append these scores to my main table.

This is the table that I will use from now on in my analysis. I want to explain what each column header means.

Country name, Regional indicator: Self explanatory

Ladder score: The "happiness score". 0 being the least happy and 10 being the most happy.

Logged GDP per capita: The log of the gdp per capita. Gdp is the value of all goods and services produced by a country in some time period. Gdp per capita is gdp divided by the population of the country. A higher value is better for this attribute.

Social support: The national average of respones to the question: If you were in trouble, do you have relatives or friends you can count on to help you whenever you need them, or not?. This is a true or false question so answers are encoded with 1 and 0; 1 meaning true/yes and 0 meaning false/no

Health life expectancy: "Average number of years that a person can expect to live in "full health" by taking into account years lived in less than full health due to disease and/or injury". This definition is from the World Health Organization.

Freedom to make life choices: The national average of respones to the question: Are you satisfied or dissatisfied with your freedom to choose what you do with your life?. The response is binary so it can be encoded as 1 or 0 like the social support response

Perceptions of corruption: The national average of respones to the following questions: "Is corruption widespread throughout the government or not?" and "Is corruption widespread within businesses or not?". The response is binary so it can be encoded as 1 or 0

depression rate: The percentage of the population that is depressed.

2021 edu index: The 2021 prediction for the education index score for a country. The education index is explained in the data collection section at the beginning of the project.

The above code displays the top 10 happiest countries and the bottom 10 happiest countries. Lets see if we can spot differences in the data. Out of the top 10 happiest countries, 9 out of 10 are in Europe while for the bottom 10, 8 out of 10 are in Africa. Why are people in Europe happier than people in Africa? We can see why if we look at the rest of the data. The top 10 countries have higher scores for logged per capita gdp, social support, healthy life expectancy, freedom to make choices, and 2021 education index when compared to the bottom 10. It is good to have high scores in these attributes which may explain why the top 10 are happier than the bottom 10. The bottom 10 have higher scores for perceptions of corruption when compared to the top 10. It is better for this score to be low which may explain why the bottom 10 are more unhappy that the top 10. For the bottom 10, depression rates are slightly lower when compared to the top 10. This is strange because you would expect that happier countries would be less depressed than unhappy countries.

The above plot is called a violin plot. Each violin is associated with a region on the x axis. The ladder score is on the y axis and the thickness of the violin illustrates the distribution of the ladder score for each region. This shows that happiness may be dependant on region which is what we observed when looking at the top 10 vs bottom 10 happiest countries.

It is good to have high scores in logged per capita gdp, social support, healthy life expectancy, freedom to make choices, and 2021 education index. For each of these attributes we can see that as their values increase, the ladder score also increases. On the other hand as the values for perseptions of corruption increase, the ladder score decreases. The depression rate does not behave as expected. As the depression rate increases, the ladder score increases. This would mean that countries that are more depressed are happier than countries that are less depressed. This does not make sense. One possible reason for this is that the poorer countries cannot spend as much money on healthcare meaning they cannot properly dignose depression.

The above plots provide some explanation as to why some countries are happier than others. Lets look at two regions: Western Europe and Sub-Saharan Africa. The violin plot shows that most of the ladder scores for Western Europe are clustered between about 6.5 and 8 while most of the ladder scores for Sub-Saharan Africa are below 5. In the previous paragraph I explained that higher scores in logged per capita gdp, social support, healthy life expectancy, freedom to make choices, and 2021 education index (good factors) seem to make countries happier. On the other hand, a high score in perceptions of corruption (bad factors) seems to make countries unhappy. As we can see from the scatter plots, the countries in Western Europe (light blue) cluster around high scores for the good factors and cluster around low scores for the bad factors. The opposite is true for countries in Sub-Saharan Africa (light green). We can use these factors to help predict the happiness of a country.

The above code gives is information that can help us contstruct a linear model. The set of predictors may change after analysis of the above output.

R-squared tells us how much the independent variable is explained by the dependent variables. The value for R-squared in this case is 0.808 which means the dependent variables explain 80.8% of the change in our independent variable. The F-statistic is a number that comes from comparing your model to a model with all zero coefficients. This is used to see if your model is statistically significant. The Prob (F-statistic) uses the F-statistic to help reject or accept the null hypothesis. The null hypothesis in this case is that a model with all zero coefficients is better than out model. If Prob (F-statistic) is less than some threshold alpha then we can reject the null hypothesis. It is common to set alpha = 0.05. If alpha = 0.05 then, in our case, Prob (F-statistic) = 3.45e-40 < 0.05 so we can reject the null hypothesis. This means our model is statistically significant.
